\begin_layout Standard
To complement the data showing county-level differences in behavior, we
 use a nationally-representative survey to show that individual behavior
 and beliefs about social distancing are partisan.
 We collect participants' demographics (including party affiliation), beliefs
 regarding the efficacy of social distancing, self-reported distancing due
 to COVID-19, and predictions about future COVID-19 cases.
 Compared to Republicans, we find that Democrats believe the pandemic is
 more severe and report a greater reduction in contact with others.
 In our survey, we also randomly vary whether predictions about future COVID-19
 cases are incentivized.
 We do not find evidence that incentives reduce the partisan gap, suggesting
 that these predictions are less likely to be due to partisan cheerleading
 (as in Bullock et al.
 2015 and Prior et al.
 2015) and more likely to reflect true differences in beliefs.
 These partisan gaps in survey responses emerge even when comparing respondents
 within the same county.
 
\end_layout

