LatexCommand label
name "sec:Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we present a stylized model to clarify why it might matter
 if different types of people choose different amounts of social distancing.
 We embed an epidemiological model of disease transmission into an economic
 model with agents who maximize utility considering the expected private
 cost of disease.
 We consider how heterogeneity in perceived risks affects aggregate welfare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Epidemiological Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use a discrete-time version of the standard SIR epidemiological model
 (Kermack and McKendrick 1927).
 In each period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, each person is in one of four states 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\{S,I,R,D\}$
\end_inset

, representing Susceptible, Infected, Recovered, and Deceased.
 The share of the population in each state at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 represent disease infectiousness, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 denote an individual's amount of risky behavior at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

—for example, the amount of travel, dining out, failing to wash hands, and
 other activities that increase the risk of becoming Infected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All people begin in the Susceptible state.
 A Susceptible person becomes Infected at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}\beta i_{t}$
\end_inset

 and stays Susceptible with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-c_{t}\beta i_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 Infected people stay Infected for one period, after which they become Deceased
 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 or Recovered with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\psi)$
\end_inset

.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are absorbing states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 index different types of people—for example, liberals and conservatives.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\theta\sigma t}$
\end_inset

 be a state variable representing the share of type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 that is in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The population is of measure 1, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\theta}\sum_{\sigma}\omega_{\theta\sigma t}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Individual Decisions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People of type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 earn flow utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\theta}(c_{t};\sigma_{t})$
\end_inset

, which depends on their risky behavior 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 and their state 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 People discount the future at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 and maximize expected lifetime utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\tau=t}^{\infty}\delta^{\tau}u_{\theta}(c_{\tau};\sigma_{\tau})$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\theta}(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 as the expected lifetime utility of a person currently in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

; note that this also implicitly depends on current and future population
 states 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\theta\sigma t}$
\end_inset

.
 Being infected reduces utility, so we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\theta}(S)>V_{\theta}(I)$
\end_inset

 for any given current population state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We focus on Susceptible people, as they comprise most of the population
 during the period we study and are the people who face a trade-off between
 the benefit of consumption and the risk of becoming infected.
 We can write their maximization problem as a Bellman equation, in which
 people maximize the sum of utility from risky behavior today and expected
 future utility:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\theta}(S_{t})=\max_{c_{t}}\left\{ \underbrace{u_{\theta}(c_{t};S_{t})}_{\text{current utility from risky behavior}}+\underbrace{\delta\left[c_{t}\beta i_{t}V_{\theta}(I)+(1-c_{t}\beta i_{t})V_{\theta}(S)\right]}_{\text{expected future utility}}\right\} .\label{eq:V}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first-order condition for privately optimal risky behavior is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underbrace{u'_{\theta}}_{\text{marginal utility of risk}}=\underbrace{\beta i_{t}}_{\text{marginal infection probability}}\underbrace{\delta\left(V_{\theta}(S)-V_{\theta}(I)\right)}_{\text{private cost of infection}}.\label{eq:FOC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first-order condition shows that people choose their risky behavior
 to equate marginal benefit (more utility today) with private marginal cost
 (higher risk of infection, which reduces future utility).
 The equation illustrates that there are three reasons why risky behavior
 might vary across types.
 First is the marginal utility of risk (or equivalently, the marginal cost
 of social distancing): for example, people vary in how much they like travel
 and dining out, as well as in how easy it is to work from home.
 Second is the marginal infection probability: for example, local infection
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 differs across geographic areas.
 Third is the private cost of infection: for example, infection is more
 harmful for people who are older or have underlying health conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Social Optimum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is difficult to know for sure whether people take too many or too few
 steps to reduce disease transmission during our study period.
 Thus, we do not consider the optimal consumption of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Instead, we hold constant the total amount of risky behavior and ask whether
 the allocation across types is optimal.
 Tangibly, this means that we are not asking, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how much social distancing should people be doing?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Instead, we are asking, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holding constant the amount of social distancing people are doing, would
 some people ideally be doing less, and others ideally be doing more?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Social welfare is the sum of utility across all people in all states:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{t}=\sum_{\theta}\sum_{\sigma}\omega_{\theta\sigma t}V_{\theta}(\sigma_{t}).\label{eq:W}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 denote the total risky behavior at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 across all people.
 The (constrained) socially optimal outcome results from maximizing 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}$
\end_inset

 subject to the constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=\bar{C}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 be the shadow price on that constraint; this reflects the loss from having
 too much or too little social distancing overall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consuming 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 imposes two types of externalities.
 First, it imposes a positive pecuniary externality, as travel, dining out,
 and other risky activities help keep firms in business and workers employed.
 Second, it imposes a negative externality by increasing the person's infection
 probability, which increases the expected stock of infected people in the
 next period (
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t+1}$
\end_inset

) and then increases other Susceptible people's infection risk.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}$
\end_inset

 denote the net externality per unit of consumption, which may be positive
 or negative; this becomes more negative as the contagion externality grows.
 We assume that these externalities are constant across people and that
 people do not account for the externalities when choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the constrained social optimum, Susceptible people's consumption of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 would satisfy the following first-order condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\underbrace{u'_{\theta}-\beta i_{t}\delta\left(V_{\theta}(S)-V_{\theta}(I)\right)}_{\text{private marginal utility}}+\underbrace{\phi_{t}}_{\text{externality}}+\underbrace{\lambda}_{\text{shadow price }}.\label{eq:FOC W}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

People who are not Susceptible do not account for transition risks.
 In the constrained social optimum, they set 
